Phase space and Poisson brackets 

We will follow the elegant approach of Zuckerman  and Witten , in order to get a
covariant derivation of the Poisson brackets. This involves defining
the phase space , as the manifold of classical solutions
of the Euler-Lagrange equations of the Lagrangian. Then in order to
define Poisson brackets, as is well known, one needs to find a
symplectic form on ; recall this is simply a closed
non-degenerate two form. The idea is that one can avoid moving into
the Hamiltonian formalism by defining a symplectic form directly from
the Lagrangian ; we sketch how this works in the general case of a
one-dimensional field theory. Consider a theory with fields 
 and an action 
