Global coordinate systems and constraints 

In the previous section we parameterised the cosets using the Cartan
decomposition, leading to a global set of coordinates
 for the phase space. Actually, this is not
quite true since  and  are identified modulo , and
hence as functions  are not continuous and hence
not smooth. This corresponds to the well known fact that one cannot cover a
circle with a single chart. Thus, strictly, the formulas involving
these coordinates at best are valid in some open region of the
circles, for example everywhere except one point, such as . A
set of Poisson brackets which do hold globally are 
 and , and these serve as a global
replacement of , which as we have explained can only be
satisfied at best everywhere except at a point. Of course all the
formulas derived actually involve only  or  and hence
are all valid globally. See Isham  for a good account of
such subtleties.

Now it is clear that the future-directed constraint  will need to
be imposed. This can be either done before or after quantization. In
the coordinates developed so far this is best done after. This is because
restricting the phase space classically to , which implies 
and , means that we will have to quantize canonical
variables of the form  which is problematic. Instead we will derive a set of
coordinates which after the restriction  still allow an easy
quantization.

To do this, we need the Iwasawa decomposition of
. This tells us that any element of the group
manifold can be written as , where , and thus the
coset  can be parameterised by . If
one proceeds to calculate the symplectic form, we get the same
expression as before except that  and
similarly for . However, now the variables  are
not periodic but take all real values. This means that if one imposes
the constraint classically the phase space restricts to three
canonical pairs of the form  or
