Comparison to Quantum Field Theory 

In the previous sections we have built up a quantum theory in ,
however we found that there are (at least) two possible theories
depending on how one imposes one of the constraints. Of course one can
also investigate quantum field theory in this space. It may prove
fruitful to compare results here with the quantum mechanics in order
to gain insight into which is the "true" quantum theory, or even if
this question is meaningful. In order to make such a comparison we
need to calculate some quantity computable in both theories. One
obvious such candidate is the amplitude for the transition of a
particle between two points in . In the QFT this will
correspond to the two-point function, or the so-called Wightman
function. 


So first we briefly outline QFT in , also see  for a
good detailed account where boundary conditions are discussed which we will not do here.
